cs.AR, cs.NE, cs.CV, cs.ET, cs.DC

This paper is likely to belong to the cs.AR (Hardware Architecture) sub-category as it focuses on the utilization of approximate multipliers to enhance the training performance of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) through simulation. Additionally, it could also belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it deals with the training of neural networks. Furthermore, it could be categorized under cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) as CNNs are commonly used in computer vision tasks. It could also be classified under cs.ET (Emerging Technologies) as approximate computing is an emerging technology. Finally, it could be categorized under cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as the use of approximate multipliers can enhance the speed and power efficiency of CNN training, which is relevant to distributed and parallel computing.
